article.headline: Minnesota ends two-game skid
article.linkText: Sprewell emerges from slump in Wolves' win
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- As a point of pride, the Minnesota Timberwolves are determined not to lose more than two consecutive games this season. "Around here, that's a no-no," Kevin Garnett said after the Timberwolves ended a two-game skid with a 105-92 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday night. "We're not going to do that this year." Latrell Sprewell emerged from a shooting slump to score 31 points, while Garnett had 29 points and 10 rebounds. Minnesota pulled away in the fourth quarter with Garnett scoring 11 of his points. Garnett said losses motivate the Timberwolves to play better. "You're not as good as you think you are," he said. "It sort of gives you a little more encouragement coming into the next game." Sprewell shot 11-for-23, including 2-for-8 from 3-point range, after averaging 10.2 points and shooting 34 percent in his previous 10 games. Sprewell had just four points on 1-for-9 shooting in a loss to Boston on Sunday. "He plays like that every night," Garnett said of Sprewell. "We've just got to get him the ball in situations. We've got to do a better job of that, getting him in positions in where he can be explosive and use his energy." Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders said Sprewell has been guilty of being a little bit lackadaisical. "He knows how he's played," Saunders said. "He came out extremely aggressive." The Sonics, who lost their season-worst fifth in a row, got 37 points from Ray Allen, who missed Sunday night's loss to Detroit because of the flu. Without Allen, Seattle tied a franchise low with 65 points against the Pistons. Allen shot 13-for-24 in 41 minutes, and Brent Barry returned in a reserve role and contributed three points in 24 minutes. He had missed 20 games with a broken finger. The Sonics are 0-5 in March and have lost eight of their last nine. Allen was coughing in the locker room after the game and said he was less than 100 percent. "My first couple times up and down the floor, I was tired and I felt it in the bottom of my throat," he said. "But then after that, my body just took over and I totally forgot all about it." The Sonics (27-37) fell 10 games under .500 and are headed to the franchise's worst season since 1985-86, when they were 31-51. "I talked about that before the game that this is about the worst it's been," said Sonics coach Nate McMillan, a former Seattle player. "But what you try and do is play. This is where we are." After Vladimir Radmanovic hit a 3-pointer for Seattle with 1:30 gone in the fourth quarter, the Timberwolves led only 79-77. Minnesota then went on a 9-0 run as Sprewell made four free throws, Troy Hudson sank an 18-footer, Sprewell made another free throw and Wally Szczerbiak scored on a putback. Seattle led 52-48 at halftime as Allen had 19 points. A putback by Jerome James cut the Timberwolves' lead to 75-71 at the end of three periods.< ^Notes: The Sonics were 5-15 in the 20 games that Barry missed with a broken ring finger on his right hand that he injured in a game against Dallas on Jan. 27. The popular Barry, in his fifth season in Seattle, received a loud ovation when he entered the game with 5:49 left in the first quarter. ... The Timberwolves are 4-3 with C Michael Olowokandi back in their starting lineup. He returned Feb. 20 after missing 36 games while recovering from arthroscopic surgery to his right knee. Olowokandi grabbed 10 rebounds. ... Minnesota outrebounded Seattle 45-35, including 14-5 in the final quarter.
